## .NET Performance Analysis — `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`

**Context:** Hot path — millions of log entries/minute. All findings elevated accordingly.

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.ToLower()/.ToUpper()` | 0 |
| `.ToLowerInvariant()/.ToUpperInvariant()` | 1 |
| `params` (code) | 1 |
| LINQ (`.Select/.Where/.Take/.Any/.Aggregate`) | 12 call sites |
| `.ToArray()/.ToList()` materializations | 2 |
| Unsealed classes | 1 (0 sealed) |
| `.Substring()` | 0 |
| `.IndexOf(string)` without `StringComparison` | 0 |
| `new Regex(` | 0 |
| `.Replace()` chains | 0 |

---

### 🔴 1. LINQ Allocations on Hot Path (12 instances)

**Impact:** Each `Humanize()` call allocates 3–6 delegate+enumerator objects through chained LINQ. At millions of calls/min, this is massive GC pressure.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L128, L140, L143, L146, L149, L158, L169, L244, L261–262, L270–272, L284, L304

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chains with `foreach` loops. Examples of the two worst sites:

`SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan` (L133–150) — 3 enumerator + 2 delegate allocations + list materialization:
```csharp
// Before (L138–149): chained .Where().Take().Where() + [.. timeParts]
// After:
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (!countEmptyUnits && part == null) continue;
        if (countEmptyUnits) count++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            result.Add(part);
            if (!countEmptyUnits) count++;
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

`IsContainingOnlyNullValue` (L127–128) — delegate + enumerator to check a `List<string?>`:
```csharp
// Before: !timeParts.Any(x => x != null)
// After:
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

`HumanizeDisplayStrings` (L266–286) — `.Select().Where().ToArray()` chain:
```csharp
// Replace with a single foreach that trims + filters into a pre-sized list
private string HumanizeDisplayStrings(IEnumerable<string?> strings, string separator)
{
    var items = new List<string>();
    foreach (var item in strings)
    {
        if (item == null) continue;
        var trimmed = item.Trim();
        if (trimmed.Length > 0) items.Add(trimmed);
    }
    // ... rest unchanged
}
```

---

### 🔴 2. Enum.ToString() + ToLowerInvariant() Per Call (1 compound instance)

**Impact:** `FormatTimePart` (L174–177) calls `unit.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` — 2 string allocations per time unit, up to 8× per `Humanize()` call. Enum `ToString()` is slow (~reflection on first call, cached but still allocates).

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L175

**Fix:** Cache the lowercase unit names in a static array:
```csharp
private static readonly string[] s_unitNames =
[
    "year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"
];

// Pre-compute singular and plural forms
private static readonly string[][] s_unitParts = s_unitNames
    .Select(n => Enumerable.Range(0, 100).Select(v =>
        v == 1 ? $"{v} {n}" : $"{v} {n}s").ToArray())
    .ToArray();

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    // Fast path for common small values
    int idx = (int)unit;
    if ((uint)value < (uint)s_unitParts[idx].Length)
        return s_unitParts[idx][value];
    var unitName = s_unitNames[idx];
    return $"{value} {unitName}s"; // value > 1 always plural
}
```

---

### 🟡 3. `params` Array Allocation (1 instance)

**Impact:** `Transform(params IStringTransformer[])` allocates an array on every call. Impactful if transformers are applied per log entry.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L302–304

**Fix:** Add a 1-argument overload for the common single-transformer case:
```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

---

### 🟡 4. Unsealed Class with Virtual Methods (1 instance)

**Impact:** `DefaultCollectionFormatter` has 4 virtual methods. Sealing enables JIT devirtualization. 0 of 1 classes sealed.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L208

**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword — `public sealed class DefaultCollectionFormatter`. **Caveat:** only if no subclasses exist elsewhere.

---

### 🟡 5. Double `.Select()` Chain in Object Formatter (1 instance)

**Impact:** `Humanize<T>(collection, Func<T, object?>, separator)` at L259–263 chains two `.Select()` calls (2 enumerator + 2 delegate allocations). Can be merged into one.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`: L259–263

**Fix:** Merge into a single `.Select()`:
```csharp
return HumanizeDisplayStrings(
    collection.Select(o => objectFormatter(o)?.ToString()),
    separator);
```

---

### ✅ Positive Findings
- ✅ No `new Regex()` per-call or `RegexOptions.Compiled` — no regex used
- ✅ No `.Substring()` calls
- ✅ No `HttpClient` or serialization concerns
- ✅ `List<string?>(8)` at L91 is pre-sized — good practice
- ✅ No sync-over-async patterns

---

### Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 2 | LINQ chains allocate 3–6 objects per `Humanize()` call; `Enum.ToString()` on every format |
| 🟡 Moderate | 3 | `params` array, unsealed class, double `.Select()` |
| ℹ️ Info | 0 | — |

**Estimated allocation reduction:** Fixing findings 1 and 2 alone could eliminate **~10–15 heap allocations per `Humanize()` call**. At millions of calls/minute, this translates to tens of millions fewer GC-tracked objects per minute.

